\end{aligned}
$$

From this formula and the identity $2 \sin \frac{\alpha}{2}= \pm \sqrt{2-2 \cos \alpha}$, it follows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
2 \sin \left(a_{1}+\frac{a_{1} a_{2}}{2}+\right. & \left.\frac{a_{1} a_{2} a_{3}}{4}+\ldots+\frac{a_{1} a_{2} \ldots a_{n} a_{n+1}}{2^{n}}\right) \frac{\pi}{4}= \\
