36. From the generalization of Cauchy's inequality, we have
$$\begin{array}{l}
(1+1+1)(1+1+1)\left[\left(\frac{1}{a}+6 b\right)+\left(\frac{1}{b}+6 c\right)+\left(\frac{1}{c}+6 a\right)\right] \geqslant \\
\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{a}+6 b}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{b}+6 c}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{c}+6 a}\right)^{3}
\end{array}$$

That is,
$$\begin{array}{l}
9\left[\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}+6(a+b+c)\right] \geqslant \\
\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{a}+6 b}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{b}+6 c}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{c}+6 a}\right)^{3}
\end{array}$$

By the AM-GM inequality, we have \(a b+b c+c a=1 \geqslant 3 \sqrt[3]{a^{2} b^{2} c^{2}}\), which implies \(\frac{1}{a b c} \geqslant 3 \sqrt{3}\).
$$\begin{array}{l}
\text { Also, }(a b)^{2}+(b c)^{2}+(c a)^{2} \geqslant a b c(a+b+c), \text { i.e., } \\
\quad \frac{1}{3 a b c} \geqslant a+b+c \\
\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}+6(a+b+c)=\frac{1}{a b c}+6(a+b+c) \leqslant \frac{1}{a b c}+\frac{2}{a b c}=\frac{3}{a b c}
\end{array}$$

Since \(\frac{1}{a b c} \geqslant 3 \sqrt{3}\), we have
$$9\left[\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}+6(a+b+c)\right] \leqslant \frac{27}{a b c} \leqslant\left(\frac{1}{a b c}\right)^{3}$$

Thus,
$$\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{a}+6 b}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{b}+6 c}+\sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{c}+6 a} \leqslant \frac{1}{a b c}$$

