If one of $x, y$ equals 1, it is also obviously true; now assume $x, y \in(1, \sqrt{\pi})$;
Since $\cos x + \cos y = 2 \cos \frac{x-y}{2} \cos \frac{x+y}{2} \leq 2 \cos \frac{x+y}{2}$, and $\frac{x+y}{2}, \sqrt{x y} \in(1, \sqrt{\pi})$, thus $\cos x + \cos y \leq 2 \cos \sqrt{x y}$, so we only need to prove: $1 + \cos x y > 2 \cos \sqrt{x y}$;

Let $t = \sqrt{x y} \in\left(1, \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2}}\right]$, the inequality to be proved becomes: $1 + \cos t^{2} - 2 \cos t > 0$. Set $f(t) = 1 + \cos t^{2} - 2 \cos t$, then $f^{\prime}(t) = -2 t \sin t^{2} + 2 \sin t$; since $1 < t \leq \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2}}$, we have $\sin t > 0$ and $\sin t^{2} > 0$, thus $f^{\prime}(t) = -2 t \sin t^{2} + 2 \sin t < 0$ for $t > 1$. Also, $f(1) = 1 + \cos 1 - 2 \cos 1 = 1 - \cos 1 > 0$.

Therefore, $f(t) > 0$ for $t \in (1, \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2}}]$, which means $1 + \cos t^{2} - 2 \cos t > 0$.

In conclusion, the original inequality holds.

